00:44:52.930 --> 00:44:56.040
Are you able to say what
years she was at MIT?

00:44:56.040 --> 00:44:57.360
JEREMY N. SMITH: Yeah.

00:44:57.360 --> 00:45:00.520
1998 to 2003.

00:45:00.520 --> 00:45:01.640
Yeah.

00:45:01.640 --> 00:45:04.130
Did I assume any
personal habits that I

00:45:04.130 --> 00:45:06.710
changed in the course
of writing this book?

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:08.637
So two categories--
one, I started

00:45:08.637 --> 00:45:10.970
doing crazy stuff because I
was hanging out with hackers

00:45:10.970 --> 00:45:13.380
and trying to report and
understand their experience.

00:45:13.380 --> 00:45:15.140
So I don't know--
how many of you

00:45:15.140 --> 00:45:18.170
kind of like Def CON or Black
Hat, those kind of conventions?

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:18.860
Yeah.

00:45:18.860 --> 00:45:21.500
So, as you know, there's
like 25,000 hackers

00:45:21.500 --> 00:45:23.090
in Vegas for the weekend.

00:45:23.090 --> 00:45:27.524
And you just kind of see
where the spirit takes you

00:45:27.524 --> 00:45:28.190
in those things.

00:45:28.190 --> 00:45:30.830
I ended up in a
shooting range that they

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:34.790
had set up like 30 minutes
out in the unincorporated land

00:45:34.790 --> 00:45:35.720
in the Vegas desert.

00:45:35.720 --> 00:45:37.910
And there's like
drone-driven skeet,

00:45:37.910 --> 00:45:40.370
people are firing cannons
they made themself.

00:45:40.370 --> 00:45:41.450
I was like-- where--

00:45:41.450 --> 00:45:44.870
I've come a long way from home.

00:45:44.870 --> 00:45:47.690
I also climbed up on the
domes at MIT and the ledges

00:45:47.690 --> 00:45:49.170
and did that kind of stuff.

00:45:49.170 --> 00:45:52.040
And I got a tour through Los
Alamos National Laboratory,

00:45:52.040 --> 00:45:52.717
which is crazy.

00:45:52.717 --> 00:45:54.800
It's like you're walking
through the Grand Canyon,

00:45:54.800 --> 00:45:58.280
you take a right, and
there's MIT guarded

00:45:58.280 --> 00:46:01.130
by people with machine guns.

00:46:01.130 --> 00:46:02.690
Those were exciting.

00:46:02.690 --> 00:46:04.550
And as for my own
personal habits, sure.

00:46:04.550 --> 00:46:06.470
I started using
email encryption.

00:46:06.470 --> 00:46:09.470
I started using full
disk encryption.

00:46:09.470 --> 00:46:13.190
I was honestly more careful when
I Googled because I was like,

00:46:13.190 --> 00:46:16.980
somebody is knowing what I'm
typing in one way or another.

00:46:16.980 --> 00:46:20.270
And I have certain
agreements of confidentiality

00:46:20.270 --> 00:46:23.750
to change identifying
details, but you guys

00:46:23.750 --> 00:46:25.250
are going to know--
or your machines

00:46:25.250 --> 00:46:27.980
are going to know
whatever I type in.

00:46:27.980 --> 00:46:32.720
And I left my phone
when I took walks.

00:46:32.720 --> 00:46:36.290
If I didn't need
it, why be tracked?

00:46:36.290 --> 00:46:39.320
You have a story like that where
the retailer has the shopping

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:40.450
history.

00:46:40.450 --> 00:46:42.930
We've all-- I'm just
going to make a guess--

00:46:42.930 --> 00:46:47.180
90% of us have
shopped at shop 666.

00:46:47.180 --> 00:46:50.480
And you realize that's
not an isolated thing.

00:46:50.480 --> 00:46:52.400
We all shop, period.

00:46:52.400 --> 00:46:56.870
And everywhere we go, that stuff
is stored, and data is forever.

00:46:56.870 --> 00:47:00.470
So that kind of made me
think about situations where

00:47:00.470 --> 00:47:03.710
I wanted to pay cash not
necessarily out of paranoia,

00:47:03.710 --> 00:47:07.640
but just out of
intentionality if you will

00:47:07.640 --> 00:47:10.070
and sort of thinking about
the price of convenience

00:47:10.070 --> 00:47:12.140
and certain obliviousness.

00:47:12.140 --> 00:47:15.230
And certainly things like
smart fridges and doorbells

00:47:15.230 --> 00:47:18.200
are pretty terrifying
to me after hanging out

00:47:18.200 --> 00:47:21.895
in internet of things village
at Def CON for a while.

